Quantifying Rater Effects, Bias, and Reliability using Summary Data

1 Introduction

Subjective scoring is a critical component in determining outcomes for elite sports, including diving. The inherent subjectivity of this process, however, introduces potential sources of measurement error, which can compromise the validity and fairness of competition results. In the context of statistical measurement theory, judges are viewed as instruments, and the quality of their scoring (the measurement) is paramount.

This report provides a quantitative analysis of judge scoring data to evaluate rater performance and identify specific measurement artifacts. The validity of competition rankings is contingent upon the reliability and impartiality of these ratings. Rater induced errors can manifest as poor reliability (e.g., intra-judge inconsistency over events) and systematic bias (e.g., rater severity/leniency, central tendency, or non-random favoritism).

The primary objective of this study is to summarize judge scoring behavior across multiple dimensions and convert these metrics into an overall performance rank using a penalty based scoring framework. Key aspects of the analysis include:

  1. Reliability and consistency, assessing how stable each judges scores are relative to the panel baseline.
  2. Bias and agreement, evaluating whether judges are systematically high or low and how closely their ranking of dives matches the panel consensus.
  3. Extremeness and scale use, quantifying how often judges give extreme scores and how they use the available scoring range, with larger departures receiving higher penalties and contributing more to the overall rank.

This analysis aims to provide objective, data driven metrics for judge assessment, supporting efforts to ensure scoring integrity and guide future rater calibration.

2 Methods

2.1 Data

2.1.1 Data Description

The dataset is a consolidated collection of scoring records from multiple diving competitions, spanning the 2024 and 2025 seasons.

The data captures the scores awarded by a panel of judges for each individual dive. Per competition rules, these scores are issued on a standard 0-to-10 scale, typically in 0.5-point increments.

A detailed description of all variables used in this analysis is provided in Appendix A.

2.1.2 Data cleaning

2.1.2.1 Merging 2024 and 2025 Data

To construct the analytic dataset, data from the 2024 and 2025 competition seasons were combined. This aggregation was performed to increase the overall sample size (\(N\)), thereby enhancing the statistical power and generalizability of the findings.

2.1.2.2 Data Deduplication and Consistency Check

To maintain data integrity, a two-stage cleaning process is implemented to isolate unique scoring events:

  1. Removal of exact duplicates: Exact duplicate rows are removed to avoid biasing variability measures and agreement metrics. There are 6304 exact duplicate rows removed in this step, leaving 67837 unique rows.

  2. Verification of judgedive uniqueness: A secondary check ensures that unique judgedive combinations (stratified by year, meet, event, and judge) do not appear more than once in the final dataset. After deduplication, no judgedive combination appears more than once, confirming data consistency.

2.1.2.3 Flag anonymous judges

An indicator variable, is_anonymous_judge, is constructed to denote observations where the judge_id is missing. This flag facilitates the handling of unidentifiable judges, allowing for their exclusion from judge-specific modeling (e.g., random effects) or for separate descriptive summarization.

2.2 Statistical Assumptions

The analysis relies on the following assumptions regarding the data and scoring process:

  1. Judge Identifiability: Individual assessment is restricted to judges with valid IDs. Anonymous data contribute to baseline calculations but are not assessed individually.
  2. Scoring Protocols: Dive scores are computed using official rules based on panel size (2, 3, 5, or 7 judges).
  3. Independence:Judges are assumed to score independently, with no collusion or dependence structure within panels.
  4. Metadata Integrity: Dive attributes (e.g., difficulty, gender, team) are assumed to be accurate and free of systematic error.
  5. Consensus Validity & Panel Sufficiency: The LOO panel aggregate serves as the proxy for true performance quality. This assumption is conditional on panel size (\(N \ge 3\)). Panels with fewer than 3 judges lack sufficient degrees of freedom to distinguish individual bias from consensus and are deemed unreliable for baseline comparison.

2.3 Statistical Analysis

This analysis is designed to provide a comprehensive, quantitative evaluation of individual judge performance in diving competitions. The objective is to quantify performance across five critical dimensions by referencing each judge against the collective judgment of their peers.

2.3.1 Leave one Judge out (LOO) Baseline

1. Objective: Creating an Independent Standard

To objectively assess the performance of any single judge, their scoring must be compared against a reliable, independent benchmark. This benchmark is established using the Leave-One-Out (LOO) method, which calculates the consensus score derived exclusively from all other judges in the panel. This effectively simulates the panels judgment if the target judge had not participated.

2. Rationale: Ensuring a Robust Consensus

The baseline must represent the true, shared agreement on a dives quality, not merely a simple average susceptible to error. A simple arithmetic mean is easily distorted by a single score that may represent a mistake, a mis-click, or an extreme outlier.

To mitigate this, the consensus is defined as a robust estimate of the panels view. When sufficient data is available, a Trimmed Mean is employed. This method excludes the most extreme high and low scores from the remaining panel before calculating the average, preventing outliers from skewing the final benchmark.

3. Methodology and Data Integrity

For each judge-dive pair \((j,d)\), the LOO Baseline (\(BL_{d(-j)}\)) is computed as follows:

\[ BL_{d(-j)} = \begin{cases} \text{TrimmedMean}(y_{kd}) & \text{if } n_{-j} \ge 3 \\ \text{Mean}(y_{kd}) & \text{if } n_{-j} = 2 \\ \text{Flagged / NA} & \text{if } n_{-j} < 2 \end{cases} \]

Where:

  • \(BL_{d(-j)}\): LOO Baseline for dive \(d\) excluding judge \(j\).
  • \(y_{kd}\): Score given by judge \(k\) for dive \(d\).
  • \(n_{-j}\): The number of judges remaining in the panel after excluding judge \(j\).

Data Quality Constraint (Handling Insufficient Panels):

Reliable consensus estimation requires a minimum number of reference points. Cases where the remaining panel size is small (\(n_{-j} < 2\), corresponding to original panels of 2 judges) are flagged and excluded from consensus-based analysis.

Specifically, in a 2-judge panel, the LOO baseline for Judge A becomes solely Judge Bs score. In this scenario, any observed deviation represents a simple difference rather than a deviation from a true consensus. It becomes statistically impossible to distinguish Judge As bias from Judge Bs bias (it is an issue of identifiability). Consequently, such records are unreliable for baseline comparison and are treated as missing values.

2.3.2 Per-Dive Residuals

For each judge-dive pair \((j,d)\), several metrics need to be calculated to capture the judges deviation from the panel baseline.

1. Residual (\(r_{jd}\)):

The raw deviation of an individual judges score from the panel baseline for a single dive.

\[ r_{jd} = y_{jd} - BL_{d(-j)} \]

Where:

  • \(r_{jd}\): Residual for judge \(j\) on dive \(d\).
  • \(y_{jd}\): Score given by judge \(j\) for dive \(d\).
  • \(BL_{d(-j)}\): LOO Baseline for dive \(d\) excluding judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • A positive \(r_{jd}\) indicates that judge \(j\) scored dive \(d\) higher than the panel baseline.
  • A negative \(r_{jd}\) indicates that judge \(j\) scored dive \(d\) lower than the panel baseline.

2. Panel Volatility (\(SD_{d(-j)}\)):

The standard deviation of the other judges. This measures how controversial the dive was. \[ SD_{d(-j)} = \text{sd}(y_{kd \in P_{d(-j)}}) \]

Where:

  • \(SD_{d(-j)}\): Standard deviation of scores for dive \(d\) excluding judge \(j\).
  • \(y_{kd}\): Score given by judge \(k\) for dive \(d\).
  • \(P_{d(-j)}\): Set of all judges who scored dive \(d\), excluding judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

If \(SD_{d(-j)}\) is very small, which means the dive was universally agreed upon, then even a small residual \(r_{jd}\) indicates a significant deviation.

3. Extremal Identity (\(is\_max_{jd}\), \(is\_min_{jd}\)):

A binary indicator (1/0) if \(y_{jd}\) was the single highest or lowest score given for dive \(d\).

  • \(is\_max_{jd} = 1\) if \(y_{jd}\) is the unique maximum score for dive \(d\).
  • \(is\_min_{jd} = 1\) if \(y_{jd}\) is the unique minimum score for dive \(d\).

4. Edge Gap (\(gap\_next_{jd}\)):

The absolute score difference between \(y_{jd}\) and the next closest panel score. This metric is non-zero only if the judge is a unique extreme (i.e., \(is\_max_{jd}=1\) or \(is\_min_{jd}=1\)). It measures how isolated the judges extreme score is from the next closest score in the same panel.

\[ gap\_next_{jd} = \begin{cases} y_{jd} - \max(y_{kd \in P_{d(-j)}}) & \text{if } is\_max_{jd} = 1 \text{ (Unique Max)} \\ \min(y_{kd \in P_{d(-j)}}) - y_{jd} & \text{if } is\_min_{jd} = 1 \text{ (Unique Min)} \\ 0 & \text{otherwise} \end{cases} \]

Where:

  • \(gap\_next_{jd}\): Edge gap for judge \(j\) on dive \(d\).
  • \(y_{jd}\): Score given by judge \(j\) for dive \(d\).
  • \(P_{d(-j)}\): Set of all judges who scored dive \(d\), excluding judge \(j\).
  • \(\max(y_{kd \in P_{d(-j)}})\): The highest score given by the other judges (the closest score to a unique max).
  • \(\min(y_{kd \in P_{d(-j)}})\): The lowest score given by the other judges (the closest score to a unique min).

This flag identifies scores that are absolutely isolated from the rest of the panel, regardless of panel volatility.

Interpretation:

A large \(gap\_next_{jd}\) indicates that judge \(j\)s extreme score is far from the next closest score, suggesting a significant outlier.

2.3.3 Judge-Level Metric Aggregation

In this phase, the per-dive metrics across all dives \(D_j\) (the set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\)) need to be aggregated to create a comprehensive performance profile.

2.3.3.1 Severity / Leniency

Measures the judges systematic bias.

\[ SEV_j = \text{mean}(r_{jd} \mid d \in D_j) \]

Where:

  • \(SEV_j\): Severity/Leniency of judge \(j\).
  • \(r_{jd}\): Residual for judge \(j\) on dive \(d\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • A positive value indicates leniency (scores usually higher than panel baseline).
  • A negative value indicates severity (scores usually lower).

2.3.3.2 Inconsistency

Measures the judges volatility or randomness.

\[ INC_j = \text{sd}(r_{jd} \mid d \in D_j) \]

Where:

  • \(INC_j\): Inconsistency of judge \(j\).
  • \(r_{jd}\): Residual for judge \(j\) on dive \(d\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • A low \(INC_j\) means the judge is predictable (even if systematically severe/lenient).
  • A high \(INC_j\) indicates the judge is erratic and noisy.

2.3.3.3 Range Utilization

Measures the judges tendency to use the full scale.

\[ SPREAD_j = \text{sd}(y_{jd} \mid d \in D_j) \]

Where:

  • \(SPREAD_j\): Range Utilization of judge \(j\).
  • \(y_{jd}\): Score given by judge \(j\) for dive \(d\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • A low value indicates a safe judge who avoids high or low scores and clusters around the center.
  • A high value indicates a judge willing to use the full range of scores.

2.3.3.4 Range Ratio

However, a raw \(SPREAD_j\) value is hard to interpret in isolation. To address this, the judges spread against the panels average spread is calculated:

\[ RR_j = \frac{SPREAD_j}{\text{mean}(SD_{d(-j)} \mid d \in D_j)} \]

Where:

  • \(RR_j\): Range Ratio of judge \(j\).
  • \(SPREAD_j\): Range Utilization of judge \(j\).
  • \(SD_{d(-j)}\): Standard deviation of scores for dive \(d\) excluding judge \(j\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • A value close to 1 indicates the judges spread matches the panel average.
  • A value less than 1 indicates the judge uses a narrower range than the panel average.
  • A value greater than 1 indicates the judge uses a wider range than the panel average.

2.3.3.5 Agreement with Panel

Measures whether the judges rank-ordering of dives aligns with the panels. A judge can have high severity (e.g., \(SEV_j = -0.5\)) but still have high agreement (\(CORR_j \approx 1\)), meaning they correctly identify good vs.bad dives but just score them all 0.5 points lower.

\[ CORR_{spearman, j} = \text{Cor}\left( \text{rank}(y_{jd}), \text{rank}(BL_{d(-j)}) \mid d \in D_j \right) \] (Spearman correlation)

Where:

  • \(CORR_j\): Agreement of judge \(j\) with panel consensus.
  • \(rank(y_{jd})\): Rank of judge \(j\)s score for dive \(d\).
  • \(rank(BL_{d(-j)})\): Rank of the LOO Baseline for dive \(d\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

  • High positive value (close to +1): Indicates strong agreement. The judges rank the dives in the same order.
  • Value close to 0: Indicates no relationship (randomness). The judges rankings are unrelated.
  • High negative value (close to -1): Indicates strong disagreement (inverse relationship). The judges rank the dives in the opposite order (one loves it, one hates it).

2.3.3.6 Extremeness

These metrics quantify how often and how far a judge is an outlier compared to the rest of the panel.

Extremal Rate (\(ER_j\)): The frequency (rate) at which the judge is the unique highest or lowest scorer on the panel. \[ \begin{aligned} ER_j^{max} &= \text{mean}(\mathbf{1}(is\_max_{jd}) \mid d \in D_j) \\ ER_j^{min} &= \text{mean}(\mathbf{1}(is\_min_{jd}) \mid d \in D_j) \end{aligned} \]

Where:

  • \(ER_j^{max}\) (Lenience Rate): Proportion of dives where judge \(j\) was the unique highest scorer.
  • \(ER_j^{min}\) (Severity Rate): Proportion of dives where judge \(j\) was the unique lowest scorer.
  • \(is\_max_{jd}\), \(is\_min_{jd}\): Indicators if judge \(j\) was the unique max or min scorer on dive \(d\).
  • \(D_j\): Set of all dives evaluated by judge \(j\).

Interpretation:

Max Rate: This measures how often the judge gives the unique highest score.

Min Rate: This measures how often the judge gives the unique lowest score.

A judge can have high \(ER_j\) which means this judge often gives the highest or lowest score, but if this judge always gives scores close to the next closest judge, the \(z_{jd}\) will be small. Thus, the extremeness is only telling if the judge is frequently an outlier, but not how much of an outlier they are. So, another metric \(EGI_j\) is needed to capture the magnitude of extremeness.

Extreme Gap Index (\(EGI_j\)): The average magnitude of the judges deviation on the occasions they were an extreme scorer. This separates a judge who is barely the highest from one who is wildly the highest.

1. Positive Extremal Gap Index (\(EGI_j^{max}\))

\[ EGI_j^{max} = \frac{\sum_{d \in D_j} \cdot gap\_next^{max}_{jd} \cdot \mathbf{1}(is\_max_{jd})}{\sum_{d \in D_j} \mathbf{1}(is\_max_{jd})} \]

Where \(gap\_next^{max}_{jd}\) is the difference between the judges score and the second highest score.

2. Negative Extremal Gap Index (\(EGI_j^{min}\))

\[ EGI_j^{min} = \frac{\sum_{d \in D_j} \cdot gap\_next^{min}_{jd} \cdot \mathbf{1}(is\_min_{jd})}{\sum_{d \in D_j} \mathbf{1}(is\_min_{jd})} \]

Where \(gap\_next^{min}_{jd}\) is the difference between the second lowest score and the judges score.

Note: EGI_j is defined only for judges with ER_j > 0; otherwise set to NA.

Where:

  • \(EGI_j\): Extreme Gap Index of judge \(j\).
  • \(z_{jd}\): Standardized Residual (calculated using LOO statistics) for judge \(j\) on dive \(d\).
  • The denominator counts the number of dives where judge \(j\) was an extreme scorer.
  • The numerator sums the absolute standardized residuals for those extreme cases.

Interpretation:

  • \(EGI_j\) is only defined if the judge has at least one extreme score (i.e., \(ER_j > 0\)). Using the standardized residual \(z_{jd}\) ensures that the extremeness is measured relative to panel volatility. This prevents judges from being unfairly penalized for scoring extreme dives where the panel itself is highly variable.

  • A high \(EGI_j\) indicates that when judge \(j\) is an outlier, they are substantially different from the rest of the panel.

  • A low \(EGI_j\) indicates that even when judge \(j\) is an outlier, they are only marginally different from the rest of the panel.

The threshold of \(EGI_j\) for flagging a judge as extremely extreme can use elbow methods or domain expertise to set a meaningful cutoff. By plotting sorted \(EGI_j\) values, the inflection point where the slope sharply increases was defined as the threshold. This point naturally separates normal panel variation from significant outliers. Any judge above this threshold is flagged as extremely extreme.

2.3.4 Integrated Performance Metrics and Composite Ranking

To provide a holistic assessment of judge performance, five key dimensions are evaluated. For each dimension, the raw metric is transformed into a Penalty Score (\(B_j^{(m)}\)), where a value of 0 represents ideal performance and larger values indicate greater deviation from the panel consensus.

Performance Metrics and Penalty Scores

The following five metrics quantify specific aspects of judging behavior. In all cases, the judges goal is to minimize the Penalty Score.

1. Severity (Syestematic Bias)

  • Metric: The mean residual \(SEV_j\).
  • Penalty Score: \(B_j^{(1)} = |SEV_j|\) (absolute deviation from zero).

Interpretation: Measures how much the judge systematically deviates from the panel baseline. Judges should aim to have no systematic bias (neither severe nor lenient).

2. Consistency (Reliability)

  • Metric: The standard deviation of residuals \(INC_j\).
  • Penalty Score: \(B_j^{(2)} = INC_j\) (lower is better).

Interpretation: Measures the judges internal consistency. Judges should aim to minimize variability in their scoring relative to the panel baseline.

3. Agreement (Ranking Order Correlation)

  • Metric: The Spearman correlation \(CORR_j\).
  • Penalty Score: \(B_j^{(3)} = 1 - CORR_j\) (higher correlation is better).

Interpretation: Measures how well the judges ranking of dives aligns with the panel consensus. Judges should aim for perfect agreement (correlation of 1).

4. Extremeness (Outlier Behavior)

  • Metric: The Extreme Gap Index \(EGI_j\).
  • Penalty Score: \[ B_j^{(4)} = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } ER_j = 0 \\ {EGI_j} & \text{if } ER_j > 0 \end{cases} \]

Interpretation: Measures how extreme the judges outlier scores are. Judges should aim to avoid being extreme outliers.

5. Range Use (Scale Utilization)

  • Metric: The Range Ratio \(RR_j\).
  • Penalty Score: \[ B_j^{(5)} = \begin{cases} RR_j & \text{if } RR_j \ge 1 \\ \frac{1}{RR_j} & \text{if } RR_j < 1 \end{cases} \]

Interpretation: Measures the consistency of the judges scoring spread relative to the panel. This piecewise formulation ensures symmetric penalties: if a judges range is narrower than the panels (\(RR_j < 1\)), the ratio is inverted (\(\frac{1}{RR_j}\)) to treat range compression and expansion equivalently. A score of 1 indicates the judges scale utilization matches the panel average.

Composite Ranking Construction

To create an overall ranking of judges, each of the five Penalty Scores is converted into a same directional rank (lower is better).

Per-Metric Ranking Rules: For each metric \(m\), judges are ranked in ascending order based on their Penalty Scores (\(B_j^{(m)}\)).

  • Rank 1: Lowest Penalty Score (best performance).
  • Ties are resolved using the min method (all tied judges receive the same best rank).

The overall rank is computed as the sum of the individual metric ranks:

\[ Overall\ Rank_j = \sum_{m=1}^{5} Rank(B_j^{(m)}) \]

Judges are ordered by \(R_j^{\text{total}}\) in ascending order. A lower total score signifies better overall performance across all evaluated dimensions.

2.4 Software

All statistical analyses and data visualizations were performed using the R (version 4.5.1) within the RStudio integrated development environment (version 2025.09.2+418).

This section provides an overview of the scoring landscape across all judges and events. By examining the full distribution of raw awards, it is possible to identify general scoring tendencies, detect unusual scoring behaviors, and establish a baseline for subsequent judge-level reliability analyses.

3.1.3.1 By examining the distribution of raw awards to understand judges overall scoring tendencies

Figure 1 shows that scores are strongly concentrated between 5 and 7 points, indicating that most dives receive mid-range marks. Very low (02) and very high (910) scores are rare. Overall, judges tend to avoid the extreme ends of the scale and score most dives in a fairly central band.

3.1.3.2 Raw score distribution by meet type

By plotting raw scores across meet types to see whether judging levels differ systematically between competition formats.

Figure 2 shows championship and dual meets tend to have slightly higher medians than other meets, while invitational meets show somewhat lower central scores and a wider spread. This suggests that meet context may be associated with modest differences in judging severity, although the distributions overlap substantially.

3.1.3.3 Relationship between DD and raw award (scatter with smooth)

This plot examines how judge scores vary across different levels of dive difficulty, highlighting whether harder dives tend to receive higher or lower raw awards.

Note: The degree of difficulty (DD) ranges from 1.2 to 3.4.

Based on Figure 3, raw awards increase only slightly with higher degree of difficulty. The smooth trend is nearly flat with a mild upward slope at high DD values, suggesting judges generally score execution similarly across difficulty levels, with only modest reward for harder dives.

3.1.3.4 Raw score distribution by diver gender

In this analysis, dives with missing or non-standard gender labels (deleted or not specified) are excluded from the dataset. This plot then compares raw scores between male and female divers to assess whether judges systematically score one group higher or lower.

Figure 4 indicates that female and male divers receive very similar score distributions, with nearly identical medians and spreads; there is no strong evidence of systematic gender-based scoring differences in raw awards.

3.2 Judge-Level Scoring Framework and Performance Metrics

This section describes how the methodology is extended to the full historical dataset. Using the procedure described in Methods, judge-level severity, inconsistency, agreement, extremeness, and range-use scores were computed for 105 identified judges. The analysis starts from per-dive standardization within each panel and then aggregates these quantities to the judge level across meets. Finally, the judge-level metrics are converted into integrated performance scores and an overall rank for each judge. Because five judges appeared only in dives where the panel size was smaller than three and thus no valid residuals could be computed, they were excluded from the judge-level analysis, leaving 100 judges in the final ranking.

3.3 Relationship between overall rank and judge-level metrics

After ranking judges by the composite performance score and listing the top and bottom panels in tables, it is helpful to see how each underlying metric changes across the full ranking. This plot treats overall rank as a continuum and shows how inconsistency, agreement, severity, range use, and extremeness evolve from the best to the worst judges.

In Figure 6, the trend lines show a clear pattern: inconsistency (INC) rises steadily with worse rank and increases sharply among the bottom judges, while agreement with the panel (CORR) drifts downward and drops more sharply in the worst decile. Severity (SEV) stays close to zero for most judges and then becomes more positive for the lowest ranks, indicating a cluster of consistently high scorers. Range-use ratio (RR) is somewhat higher in the middle of the ranking but does not separate the extremes as strongly, whereas edge-importance (EGI) gradually increases and then spikes for the lowest-ranked judges, suggesting that their disagreements with the panel tend to occur on more consequential dives.

3.4 Comparison of key metrics for top vs bottom judges

Given the continuous patterns above, a direct side-by-side comparison of the best and worst judges helps quantify how far apart these groups really are. This figure focuses on the top 10 and bottom 10 judges and compares their distributions for the same set of metrics.

Based on Figure 7, the bottom 10 judges show noticeably higher inconsistency and more positive severity, while the top 10 cluster around lower INC values and SEV close to zero. Agreement with the panel is much stronger for the top group, with CORR tightly concentrated at high values, whereas the bottom group has both lower medians and more spread. The bottom judges also tend to have slightly larger range-use ratios, and their EGI values are clearly higher and more variable, suggesting that their disagreements with the panel occur more often on influential dives. Taken together, inconsistency, agreement, severity, and edge importance are the main features distinguishing the best and worst judges.

3.5 Correlation between overall rank and judge-level metrics

After visualizing patterns in the raw metrics, a compact summary of their association with the composite rank helps clarify which dimensions drive the ranking most strongly. The bar chart reports Spearman correlations between overall rank and each metric, treating higher ranks (larger numbers) as poorer performance.

Figure 8 shows overall rank is most strongly and positively associated with edge importance (EGI), followed closely by inconsistency (INC), suggesting that judges who fall lower in the ranking tend both to disagree with their panels on more consequential dives and to be more variable overall. Agreement with the panel (CORR) shows a strong negative correlation, meaning lower-ranked judges deviate more from the consensus. Severity (SEV) has a modest positive correlation with rank, while range-use ratio (RR) is only weakly related, reinforcing that EGI, INC, and CORR are the primary drivers of the composite ordering.

3.7 Judge-Level Bias Analyses

This section evaluates whether judges score certain groups of dives more favorably than others after controlling for panel baselines. Detailed judge lists can be provided in an appendix.

3.7.1 Gender-Based Scoring Differences

For each judge, the average residual on girls dives is compared with the average residual on boys dives. A positive difference indicates more generous scoring for girls; a negative difference indicates more generous scoring for boys.

Figure 9 indicates that most judges sit very close to zero on this gender-bias index, so their average scores for girls and boys are almost the same. The bulk of the distribution is just slightly on the positive side, suggesting a small tendency to score girls a bit higher, and only a few judges show clearly stronger bias in either direction, including one clear negative outlier.

Based on Figure 11, for most judges, the difference between low and high difficulty residuals is close to zero, indicating stable severity across difficulty levels once the panel baseline is removed. A limited number of judges show shifts of about 0.5 points or more, suggesting that harder dives are scored systematically higher or lower than easier dives for those individuals.

3.7.3 Meet-Type Effects on Judge Scoring

To assess whether judges change severity across competition settings, a meet-type spread is computed for each judge as the difference between the highest and lowest mean residual across meet types (for example, dual meets, invitationals, championships).

The histogram in Figure 11 shows the spread in mean residuals for all eligible judges. Most judges cluster near 0 to 0.10, meaning they show only small shifts in severity between meet types. However, a noticeable tail extends beyond 0.30, with a few judges changing their scoring behavior substantially depending on the setting.

3.7.4 Team-Level Preferences in Scoring

Team-level bias is evaluated by comparing, for each judge, the mean residual for a specific team with the mean residual for all other teams combined, using only judgeteam combinations with sufficient dives in both groups.

In Figure 12, team-related differences are small and centered near zero, indicating that divers from one team generally receive similar scores to divers from other teams after adjusting for the panel. A few judgeteam pairs exhibit larger differences ( > 1 point); these appear as isolated relationships that may merit monitoring rather than a broad pattern of favoritism or severity.

4 Conclusion

This report establishes a statistical framework designed to quantify and monitor the quality of diving judging. By analyzing over 44,000 scores from the 20242025 seasons, the study evaluates officials across five critical dimensions: severity, inconsistency, extremeness, agreement, and scoring range. Additionally, the analysis produces specific performance rankings for all identified judges. This framework serves as a scalable foundation for the Dive+ app ecosystem. It provides an effective mechanism to integrate advanced quality assurance features into the system and ensures a more robust, data-driven experience for the diving community.

Appendix

Appendix A

Analytic Data Dictionary

Judge Identifiers

judge_id: Unique user id for a judge, a null/blank value means the judge was anonymous

judge_user_fullname: Judges full name

judge_number: The chair in which the judge sat 1-7

Meet & Event Identifiers

meet_id: Unique identifier for the meet (competition).

meet_name: Official name of the meet.

meet_type: Category of the meet (dual, championship, invitational, mock).

meet_date: Last date of the meet.

meet_location: City, state of the meet

event_id: Unique identifier for the specific event (e.g., an ID for boys 1 meter).

event_name: Description of the event (e.g., Girls 1m high school).

Diver & Team Identifiers

diver_id: Unique identifier for the diver.

diver_gender: Gender of the diver (e.g., M, F).

diver_team_id: Unique identifier for the divers team.

team_name: Full name of the divers team

team_abbreviation: Abbreviated name of the divers team

sheet_id: Identifier for the original scoresheet, often unique to a diver in an event.

dive_user_fullname: Full name of the diver.

coach_id: Unique user id of the coach on the dive sheet.

coach_fullname: Full name of the coach on the dive sheet.

submitted_dive_id: Unique id of a dive competed in a meet.

round_number: Round number of the dive (1-11).

dive_round_id: Unique round id of a dive on a sheet.

dive_code: Dive number (e.g., 105, 201, 403).

dive_position: Positional letter of the dive code (e.g., A, B, C, D).

Dive_height: Height of the platform or board (e.g., 1M, 3M).

dive_direction: Directional group of the dive (e.g., forward, back, reverse, inward).

dd: The numeric Degree of Difficulty (DD) for the dive.

dive_dd_id: Unique id of a dive difficulty of the dive number, position, height, and governing body.

Short_description: Abbreviated text description of the dive.

Description: Full text description of the dive.

Score Variable (Dependent Variable)

raw_award: The individual score (0-10) given by the judge for the dive. This is the primary raw score before any calculations (e.g., dropping high/low scores or multiplying by DD).

Judge Performance Metrics

Number of dives: Total count of dives included in the analysis for which a leave-one-out panel baseline was computable.

Severity: The arithmetic mean of the residuals (defined as the judges score minus the leave-one-out panel baseline).

Inconsistency: The standard deviation of the judges residuals across all analyzed dives.

Agreement with panel: The Spearman rank correlation coefficient between the judges scores and the leave-one-out panel baselines.

Extremeness rate: The proportion of dives where the judge awarded the unique maximum or unique minimum score within the panel.

Range-use ratio: The ratio of the judges raw score standard deviation to the average within-panel standard deviation of the other judges.
